<TITLE> ACC sues former chief conservator of forests </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 23 (bdnews24.com)  The country's graft watchdog Tuesday filed a case against the country's former top conservator. Anticorruption Commission assistant director SM Shahidur Rahman filed the case with Ramna police against former chief conservator of forests Munshi Anwarul Islam on charges of providing false information and acquiring assets worth Tk 2.59 crore beyond his stated income. Munshi Anwar is now in jail. Ohiduzzaman, assistant sub-inspector of Ramna police, told bdnews24.com that the former forestry boss earned about Tk 30.5 lakh from wages during his entire service life. He should not have any savings after spending on daily expenditures and on his five children's education and marriage, he said. According to case details, the former CCF spent Tk 9.92 lakh just on tuition fees for his children at different private universities and medical colleges. Officials allege that Munshi Anwar concealed assets worth Tk 82.45 lakh in his wealth statement submitted to the ACC. No sources of income have been found for the former CCF's assets worth Tk 2.59 crore. Munshi Anwar Hossain joined the government services on Jan 4, 1973. He became the deputy chief conservator of forests on Oct 29, 2002. He served as chief conservator of forests from Jan 29, 2004 until his retirement on Aug 30, 2005. bdnews24.c
